text=>>comment%3c%3c%0aSummary: Our power isn&rsquo;t in our ability to fight life. It&rsquo;s in recognizing when we don't have to struggle.%0aTags: saved page, buddhism, tinybuddha, power, struggle%0a(:tags-hide saved page, buddhism, tinybuddha, power, struggle:)%0a(:title Tiny Wisdom: Stop Fighting and Be Easy | Tiny Buddha:)%0aCategories: [[!Humanism]]%0aParent:(Main.)SpiritualityAndBeliefs%0aIncludeMe:[[Main.SpiritualityAndBeliefs]]%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:linebreaks:)%0aSource: http://tinybuddha.com/quotes/tiny-wisdom-stop-fighting-and-be-easy/%0aPage saved at: Sun, 01 Jul 2012 00:22:05 -0500%0a(:nolinebreaks:)%0a%0a(:nolinkwikiwords:)%0a%0ahttp://cdn.tinybuddha.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Buddha8.jpg%0a%0a''by Lori Deschene''%0a%0a'''&ldquo;If you surrender completely to the moments as they pass, you live more richly those moments.&rdquo; ~Anne Morrow Lindbergh'''%0a%0aThere was a time when I was full of angst, and desperate to unleash it.%0a%0aSince I felt misunderstood in some of my relationships, I&rsquo;d fight battles I knew I wouldn&rsquo;t win and then only consider letting go after a mini emotional break down.%0a%0aI needed to tire myself out in order to surrender. I needed to fully defuse my distress to give myself some peace. Though I wouldn&rsquo;t have admitted it, I was addicted to that drama. It was only when I broke down that I felt any relief.%0a%0aMost of the time, I carried my anguish in my body, like a thick layer of nerves right below the surface. I was a constantly bubbling volcano, eager to erupt.%0a%0aI no longer fight through life in this way, but there are times when I feel a pervasive sense of alarm, a low-level sense of nervousness that is lessened but not fully eliminated through meditation.%0a%0aIt&rsquo;s usually when responsibilities and deadlines are piling up, and I worry that it won&rsquo;t all get done.%0a%0aBut the thing is: It always does. And it&rsquo;s not usually because of worrying, over-analyzing, or any other type of stressful mental activity.%0a%0aThings get done because I am capable&mdash;not because I fight to finish.%0a%0aWhat I&rsquo;ve learned is that surrender doesn&rsquo;t have to follow battle. It doesn&rsquo;t have to be a side effect of exhausting ourselves in some way, mentally, physically, or emotionally.%0a%0aSurrender is a choice to be easy, to nurture a sense of inner calm that can carry us through even the most difficult circumstances.%0a%0aIt&rsquo;s choosing not create drama where it doesn&rsquo;t need to be, and realizing life doesn&rsquo;t have to feel like a series of conflicts and crises.%0a%0aIt&rsquo;s letting go of the need for control and realizing that, whatever happens, we&rsquo;ll be okay.%0a%0aIt&rsquo;s easier to say, &ldquo;Be easy,&rdquo; than it is to actually do it, ironically, because it takes effort to stop expelling so much effort&mdash;to refrain from spinning in circles in our heads and simply take life as it comes at us.%0a%0aThe good news is that we have countless opportunities to practice easing in the moment.%0a%0aIt helps when we remember: Our power isn&rsquo;t in our ability to fight life. It&rsquo;s in recognizing when we don&rsquo;t have to struggle.%0a%0a''Photo by [[http://www.drunkenfist.com/ | Rob Larson]]''%0a%0a%0aAll content Copyright tinybuddha.com%0a(:linkwikiwords:)%0a
