 that it won&rsquo;t all get done.%0a%3c %0a%3c But the thing is: It always does. And it&rsquo;s not usually because of worrying, over-analyzing, or any other type of stressful mental activity.%0a%3c %0a%3c Things get done because I am capable&mdash;not because I fight to finish.%0a%3c %0a%3c What I&rsquo;ve learned is that surrender doesn&rsquo;t have to follow battle. It doesn&rsquo;t have to be a side effect of exhausting ourselves in some way, mentally, physically, or emotionally.%0a%3c %0a%3c Surrender is a choice to be easy, to nurture a sense of inner calm that can carry us through even the most difficult circumstances.%0a%3c %0a%3c It&rsquo;s choosing not create drama where it doesn&rsquo;t need to be, and realizing life doesn&rsquo;t have to feel like a series of conflicts and crises.%0a%3c %0a%3c It&rsquo;s letting go of the need for control and realizing that, whatever happens, we&rsquo;ll be okay.%0a%3c %0a%3c It&rsquo;s easier to say, &ldquo;Be easy,&rdquo; than it is to actually do it, ironically, because it takes effort to stop expelling so much effort&mdash;to refrain from spinning in circles in our heads and simply take life as it comes at us.%0a%3c %0a%3c The good news is that we have countless opportunities to practice easing in the moment.%0a%3c %0a%3c It helps when we remember: Our power isn&rsquo;t in our ability to fight life. It&rsquo;s in recognizing when we don&rsquo;t have to struggle.%0a%3c %0a%3c ''Photo by [[http://www.drunkenfist.com/ | Rob Larson]]''%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c All content Copyright tinybuddha.com%0a%3c (:linkwikiwords:)%0a
